<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-02-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="224" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d224">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Day</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">White</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-02-07"><hi rend="italic">February 7,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Closing part of fruit decree authorizes imperial chancellor to make
                            exceptions to the prohibition and regulate precautionary measures. Does
                            this enable merchants to be heard in their own behalf, and thus obtain
                            relief in favorable cases and admission of goods where not infected?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Day</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Acting.</hi></signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>